name: Amit Paranjape
text:
Thread... testing is very important for #COVID19, and we need to significantly improve the numbers here.

But we also need proper planning of the testing infrastructure to go with it. https://t.co/IkN0VNkE8z

name: Amit Paranjape
text: Policy makers and local authorities need to work with private testing players to scale up capacity rapidly - and then scale up requirements on testing - RT-PCR/Antigen/etc.

name: Amit Paranjape
text:
Just like for vaccines, hospital beds, oxygen ...we need better planning for the testing infrastructure.

Testing requirements need to scale up along with the infrastructure - the two cannot be out of sync (as we have noticed in some places).

name: Amit Paranjape
text:
We cannot suddenly boost testing (by mandating a variety of different sets of people...e.g. industry workers take biweekly tests) - WITHOUT properly planning for 2 and 3!

Today, we are seeing long lines at testing centers and kits shortages, due to improper capacity planning.

name: Amit Paranjape
text:
As we scale up testing we need to think about -

1. The right mix of RT-PCR vs. Rapid Antigen (and decide the right use-cases for both...)

2. Lab capacity for RT-PCR (machine capacity, technician, sample collection capacity).

3. Availability of RT-PCR and Antigen Kits.

name: Amit Paranjape
text:
Testing is very important in combating the #COVID19 pandemic. Some countries have run huge city/region wide mass testing programs.

There are two main types of tests - RT-PCR and Rapid Antigen. Both tests have their advantages / disadvantages, depending on the specific use.

If you are going for essential work to any crowded place (shops, hospital, public transport, etc.)...better to wear a good quality N95/surgical mask, compared to a cloth mask. 

The prices have come down significantly (under Rs 40 for N95... under Rs 10 for Surgical Mask).

name: Amit Paranjape
text:
In fact, even inside your house - if you have old people with comorbidities and risk factors - best to limit interactions with them, without masks. 

At best masks are a minor inconvenience. But by wearing one while speaking with the old, at risk - you are protecting them.

name: Amit Paranjape
text:
And this is a request for everyone else as well. 

If you are meeting anyone outside the people in your house (office colleagues, friends, relatives, etc.) ...don't remove your masks!

This is especially true for large indoor gatherings. More the people - greater the risk.

name: Amit Paranjape
text:
No need to remove the mask when interacting with media ...we can hear you perfectly well with the mask on.

Remember - you are setting an example for everyone else, who is watching you on the screen (video/photos). 

Please set the right example! Thanks.

name: Amit Paranjape
text:
A request to politicians, celebrities, journalists, and other public figures:

Can you please wear a proper mask in meetings, in public interactions, etc.?

And please, can we all avoid this - 'removing mask just for the photo' bit? Sending the right signal is important!

Thanks

"Most treatments like plasma, Remdesivir or others either don‚Äôt work or at best improve recovery by a day or two but don‚Äôt save lives. Every COVID-19 case should remember it‚Äôs a 2-week time-table and be rested for at least 2-3 weeks based on medical advice."

(via @IndianExpress)

name: Amit Paranjape
text: "Clearly, we need to focus on saving lives and, without panic, organising digitally or physically supervised medical health care. Our healthcare facilities need to triage the most deserving cases and avoid asymptomatic or mild symptomatic cases in hospitals so we can keep beds.."

name: Amit Paranjape
text: "The simplest and easiest test is to measure the oxygen saturation on a simple pulse oximeter and after a 6-min walk record the reading ‚Äî if it is below 94% or shows a fall of 3% you need to contact a health care facility and provider to seek oxygen, steroid and supervised care."

text:
Cricket needs to look at the model followed for the commentary in U.S. leagues like the NFL.

The most common format is pairing one specialist commentator with a retired great (who is also a good commentator).

The balance is nice and effective.

name: Amit Paranjape
text:
The Best! Richie Benaud - My all-time favorite commentator. Few even come close. 

Sadly, standards are dropping each year. Many good ex-players are pretty bad at commentary.

Need more specialists (like @bhogleharsha) ... ideally a good mix of specialists and retired greats. https://t.co/1rOA55Ba9R
